Comparison of EmptyDrops to CRLikeEmptyDrops

Ally Hawkins for CCDL

In this notebook, we are exploring different methods of filtering the output of Alevin-fry when using the --unfiltered-pl option, meaning all identified cell barcodes are included in the output.

The filtering techniques we are interested in exploring are DropletUtils::emptyDrops() and DropletUtils::emptyDropsCellRanger(). Use of DropletUtils::emptyDrops() is in an attempt to more closely mirror the filtering performed in Cell Ranger and StarSolo’s emptyDrop like filtering.

Previously, use of DropletUtils::emptyDrops() with default parameters resulted in much higher numbers of cells being kept in the filtered sce and of the cells that are identified in Alevin-fry and not in Cell Ranger, those cells have lower counts and genes/cell.

Perform Filtering

EmptyDrops

Here we are going to use DropletUtils::emptyDrops() to perform filtering using the default threshold of lower=100 and testing the threshold of lower=200. The lower parameter is used to dictate which cells are chosen to create the ambient profile and represents the lower bound on the total UMI count at which all barcodes are assumed to correspond to empty droplets. Using this ambient RNA pool, the emptyDrops() function tests whether the expression profile of each cell barcode is significantly different from the ambient RNA pool or not.

# use scpcaTools::filter_counts() to filter sces 
emptydrops_filter_sces <- purrr::map(fry_sces, ~ filter_counts(sce = .x, lower = 100))

cellRangerLikeEmptyDrops

Next, we will create a list of filtered sces using the DropletUtils::emptyDropsCellRanger() function with the default settings. Currently, this function is not supported in the DropletUtils() package avaliable from Bioconductor. The version that I am using can be found at MarioniLab/DropletUtils#cellranger and was installed by cloning the repo and locally building the package.

# custom function for filtering using emptyDropsCellRanger
filter_counts_crlike <- function(sce, fdr_cutoff = 0.01){
  # round needed before emptyDropsCellRanger as a non-round matrix doesn't work right now 
  counts <- round(counts(sce))
  empty_df <- DropletUtils::emptyDropsCellRanger(m = counts)
  cells <- rownames(empty_df)[which(empty_df$FDR <= fdr_cutoff)]
  sce <- sce[, cells]
}

crlike_filter_sces <- purrr::map(fry_sces, ~ filter_counts_crlike(sce = .x))
readr::write_rds(crlike_filter_sces, file.path(results_dir, "alevin-fry-cr-like-em-cr-filtering-sces.rds"))

Knee Filtering

Let’s also see what would happen if we were to perform knee based filtering on these samples and how that would compare to the cells found in CellRanger. It’s likely that this may discard more cells than we anticipate and result in filtering that is too stringent, but it is worth taking a look at the knee plots for reference.

# make a knee plot, plotting the inflection point for each sample in Alevin-fry
plot_knee <- function(sce, sample) {
  ranks <- DropletUtils::barcodeRanks(counts(sce))
  ranks_df <- ranks %>%
    as.data.frame()
  
  ggplot(ranks_df, aes(x = rank, y = total)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_hline(yintercept = metadata(ranks)$inflection, color = "red") +
    scale_y_log10() +
    scale_x_log10() + 
    ggtitle(sample)
}

purrr::map2(fry_sces, names(fry_sces), plot_knee)

# filter using the inflection point 
knee_filter <- function(sce) {
  ranks <- DropletUtils::barcodeRanks(counts(sce))
  cells <- rownames(ranks[which(ranks$total > metadata(ranks)$inflection),])
  sce <- sce[,cells]
}

knee_filtered_sces <- fry_sces %>%
  purrr::map(knee_filter)

readr::write_rds(knee_filtered_sces, file.path(results_dir, "alevin-fry-cr-like-em-knee-filtering-sces.rds"))

Compare Cells between EmptyDrops and cellRangerLikeEmptyDrops

Now that we have performed the different filtering strategies we are ready to compare the cells that remain after filtering. We will first take a look at the number of cells that remain post filtering and compare those numbers to the Cell Ranger results. Then we will look at the distribution of UMI/cell and genes/cell with different filtering strategies in comparison to Cell Ranger.

Number of Cells Filtered

# function to grab the number of cells from an sce object

Here you can see that emptyDropsCellRanger() actually does appear to give more comprable cell numbers to Cell Ranger than emptyDrops(). Additionally, as expected, using the knee-based method decreases the numbers of cells across the board. It appears that emptyDrops() with lower=200 or lower=500 is the most comparable to Cell Ranger for all samples and we see that those cell numbers tend to be fairly similar.

Per Cell QC Metrics

Previously we had seen that cells identified in Alevin-fry, but not in Cell Ranger, led to a decrease in the median UMI/cell and genes detected/cell. However, if we now filter our cells to begin with a more similar population to Cell Ranger, do we see that the distribution of UMI/cell and genes detected/cell is on par with Cell Ranger, or is it still lower across the board?
